<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-11-26T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-11-26T21:00:00-05:00" n="401" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d401">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/7440: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-11-27T10:00:00+08:00">November 27, 1935—10
                                    a.m.</date><lb/>[Received November 27—6:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>179. Three hundred and fifteen Japanese infantry troops have arrived in
                            Peiping during the past 2 days and are billeted at the Japanese Club
                            which is in the city outside of the Legation quarter. (The regular
                            Japanese garrison numbers 321 and is billeted in the Japanese Embassy
                            guard.) The new arrivals are without special equipment.</p>
                        <p>2. Reliable information has just been received that a Japanese troop
                            train of 17 cars passed through Shanhaikwan this morning from the north,
                            destination at present unknown.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Nanking and Tokyo.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>